      "question": "If $\\cos \\theta + \\sin \\theta = \\sqrt{2} \\cos \\theta$, then find the value of $\\cos \\theta - \\sin \\theta$.",
      "answer": "$\\sqrt{2} \\sin \\theta$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Square both sides of the given equation to eliminate the radical and create an identity-friendly expression.",
          "Use the identity $\\sin^2 \\theta + \\cos^2 \\theta = 1$ to rearrange the terms and isolate the required expression."
        ],
        "derivation": "$(\\cos \\theta + \\sin \\theta)^2 = (\\sqrt{2} \\cos \\theta)^2 \\\\ \\cos^2 \\theta + \\sin^2 \\theta + 2 \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta = 2 \\cos^2 \\theta \\\\ 1 + 2 \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta = 2 \\cos^2 \\theta \\\\ \\text{Let } x = \\cos \\theta - \\sin \\theta \\\\ x^2 = (\\cos \\theta - \\sin \\theta)^2 = \\cos^2 \\theta + \\sin^2 \\theta - 2 \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta \\\\ x^2 = 1 - 2 \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta \\\\ \\text{From the first equation, } 2 \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta = 2 \\cos^2 \\theta - 1 \\\\ x^2 = 1 - (2 \\cos^2 \\theta - 1) = 2 - 2 \\cos^2 \\theta = 2(1 - \\cos^2 \\theta) = 2 \\sin^2 \\theta \\\\ x = \\sqrt{2} \\sin \\theta$"
      },
